<tr><td class="printline">
<span class="name"><a name="97510"></a></span><span class="postdetails">#8:&nbsp;<font color=black><b></b> Author:&nbsp;<b>Unmei</b>,&nbsp;</font></span><span class="postdetails"><font color=black></font></span>
<a href="viewtopic.php?p=97510#97510"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails"><font color=black>Posted: Wed Feb 23, 2005 2:00 pm</font><span class="gen"><br>
</td></tr>
<tr><td class="printline">
<span class="postbody">Toggle between self and target is one of those keybindings that sounds completely worthless, but because it works in a really strange way, is actually helpful if you can learn to do it.  Here's why:
<br />

<br />
Target something...maybe it's the mob you have charmed.  Hit your Self/Target key.  You now have yourself targetted.
<br />

<br />
Now target something else entirely. Buff your whole group one at a time  or whatever you want.  Finish with the cleric.
<br />

<br />
Now target yourself again, and hit your Self/Target key again.  Oddly, you -don't- get the cleric.  You get the mob you have charmed.
<br />

<br />
This is completely counterintuitive (to me, at least) but the net effect is that you can "save" a target, and go back to it with two keystrokes (F1, then Self/Target) whenever you want. Regardless of whether it's anywhere near you, or whatever.
<br />

<br />
Admittedly, I don't use this often, but's handy when I do.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
</td></tr>
<br />
